sec.p:
Unlike traditional MoE models that perform hard routing, we adopt a soft routing mechanism via a gating network. The gating module receives a global context vector (e.g., pooled features from the shared encoder or a separate attention summary) and outputs a soft weight vector $w=[w 1, w 2, w 3]$ via a softmax layer. These weights determine the contribution of each expert:
\begin{equation*}
F_{\text {fused }}=\sum_{i=1}^{3} w_{i} \cdot F_{i}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $F_{i}$ denotes the feature vector from the $i^{\text {th }}$ expert, and $w_{i}$ is its corresponding weight produced by the gating network. The gating module will be jointly trained with the experts using a combined loss function defined in Equation~(\ref{eqn2}).
\begin{equation*}
L_{\text {total }}=L_{\text {cls }}+\lambda \cdot L_{\text {gate-reg }}+\mu \cdot L_{\text {expert-indep }}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

•
$L_{\text {total }}$: binary cross-entropy loss for final liveness classification.
•
$L_{\text {gate-reg: }}$: optional entropy regularization to encourage confident gating decisions.
•
$L_{\text {expert-indep }}$: optional penalty to encourage diversity in expert representations.
